    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most sellers have a rough idea that selling a property involves photography and a listing on the internet, but the mechanics of how a campaign actually works are less understood than agents often assume. Knowing what happens, in what order, and why each component matters helps sellers make better decisions about where to spend, what to approve, and what to expect from the agent they appoint.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The components of a standard Brisbane campaign</h2>
      <p>A standard marketing campaign for an inner-east Brisbane property in the $1 million to $2 million range typically includes the following components: professional photography (stills and in most cases a video walkthrough), a floor plan, a copywritten property description, a listing on realestate.com.au at a standard tier, a sign board at the property, and distribution to the agency's own database of buyers. Most agents will also run some social media promotion, either through the agency's own channels or via paid advertising on Meta platforms.</p>

      <p>That is the baseline. Beyond it, agents will often recommend upgrades: a premium or Premiere listing on realestate.com.au, which provides significantly better placement in search results and can meaningfully increase listing views; professional property styling; a virtual tour or 3D walkthrough; drone photography if the land or location warrants it; and additional paid digital advertising. Each of these has a genuine rationale, and each adds cost.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Standard versus premium listing packages: whether they are worth it</h2>
      <p>The most significant upgrade decision most sellers face is whether to pay for a Premiere listing on realestate.com.au. A standard listing competes with every other standard listing in the area. A Premiere listing appears above standard listings in search results, often with larger photo tiles and more prominent placement. For inner-east Brisbane properties in competitive price ranges, the difference in enquiry volume between a standard and Premiere listing is often measurable.</p>

      <p>Whether the cost is justified depends on the property. A tightly held street with three comparable listings that go under offer in two weeks regardless does not necessarily need a Premiere listing to achieve a strong result. A property that needs to attract buyers from across Brisbane, or that is competing against several comparable listings in the same period, will benefit more substantially from the additional visibility.</p>

      <p>A good agent will give you a data-supported recommendation rather than automatically recommending the most expensive package for every property. Ask them how their comparable sales performed at different listing tiers and what the enquiry and attendance data showed.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Typical marketing costs for an inner-east Brisbane property</h2>
      <p>Marketing is a separate cost from agent commission and is typically paid by the seller upfront or deducted from the proceeds at settlement, depending on the agency agreement. For a standard campaign on an inner-east Brisbane property, marketing costs typically fall between $3,000 and $6,000. A campaign with a Premiere listing, professional styling, drone photography, and paid social advertising might run to $8,000 to $12,000.</p>

      <p>These numbers are not universal. Agents have different arrangements with their preferred suppliers, and the quality of photography and videography varies considerably even within similar price points. It is worth asking to see examples of campaigns the agent has run at similar marketing budgets before committing to a package.</p>

      <p>The cost of not marketing adequately is harder to quantify than the cost of marketing well, but it is real. A poorly presented listing that does not attract sufficient buyer interest in the first two to three weeks creates its own problems: extended days on market, price reductions, and buyer perception that something is wrong with the property. The upfront cost of a well-resourced campaign is almost always cheaper than the cost of a campaign that underperforms and needs to be relaunched.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The marketing schedule: what happens and when</h2>
      <p>Once you have signed the agency agreement and agreed on a marketing budget, the campaign typically runs on a schedule that looks like this. In the first week, the agent will arrange photography, usually within two to four days of the agreement being signed. The photographer and videographer will need the property to be in final presentation condition on the day of the shoot; this is not the time for work to still be in progress.</p>

      <p>The listing copy is usually drafted by the agent or a copywriter and should be reviewed and approved by the seller before the listing goes live. It is worth taking this step seriously. The written description shapes how buyers who are filtering by keywords and scanning listings quickly form their first impression. Ask for changes if the description does not accurately represent the property or if it misses features that matter to buyers.</p>

      <p>The listing typically goes live four to seven days after the agreement is signed, depending on how quickly photography and approvals are finalised. The first open home is usually scheduled for the first weekend after the listing goes live. The open home schedule then runs weekly, typically on Saturdays, for the duration of the campaign. Private inspections can be arranged through the week for buyers who cannot attend open homes.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Off-market pre-marketing before public launch</h2>
      <p>Many experienced agents conduct a pre-marketing phase before the property goes live publicly. This involves contacting the agency's existing database of qualified buyers, particularly those who have missed out on recent comparable sales, to preview the property before the listing appears on portals.</p>

      <p>Pre-marketing has genuine advantages. It creates a sense of exclusivity and can generate early competition among buyers who have been actively searching for several months. It also allows the agent to test buyer response and pricing assumptions before the broader market sees the property. If offers are made during pre-marketing, a seller can choose to accept, negotiate, or proceed to a public campaign with the benefit of knowing there is existing buyer interest.</p>

      <p>The limitation of pre-marketing is that it is limited to buyers already known to the agency. If the most motivated buyer for your property is not yet in the agency's database, pre-marketing alone will not reach them. For most properties, pre-marketing works best as a supplement to a public campaign rather than a replacement for one.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers can and cannot influence</h2>
      <p>Sellers have significant influence over some parts of the campaign and almost none over others. The things sellers control directly are: the presentation state of the property before photography and at every open home, their availability to approve copy and photos before the listing goes live, the asking price or price range (or the reserve price, in the case of an auction), and the timing of accepting an offer.</p>

      <p>The things sellers cannot control are: how many buyers are actively looking for their property type in their suburb at the time of listing, what the competition from other listings looks like during the campaign period, the specific day-to-day activity in the market, and how individual buyers behave during negotiations. Trying to manage or second-guess these variables is rarely productive. The variables sellers control matter far more to the outcome than the variables they do not.</p>

      <p>The most common seller mistake during a campaign is micro-managing the agent on the things that cannot be controlled while being less engaged on the things that can: preparation quality, turnaround on copy approvals, and open home presentation. Getting those fundamentals right consistently produces better results than worrying about whether enquiry volume in week two is slightly below what the agent projected in week one.</p>

